  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3335819061" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3335819061" />
    <a title="Klaus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/83849229-klaus"><img alt="Klaus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618916901p2/83849229.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3335819061?book_show_action=true">May 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Klaus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Klaus" href="/user/show/83849229-klaus">Klaus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83849229-klaus?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83849229-klaus?shelf=heist">heist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83849229-klaus?shelf=lynch">lynch</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83849229-klaus?shelf=ya-fantasy">ya-fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3335819061" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3516815020184661659">26/25 (104%) 5 stars.<br/><b> Well. Whenever I&apos;ve read an author&apos;s first book and simply adored it, like I did with Lynch&apos;s first, I&apos;m really, really afraid that the next one won&apos;t live up to the high expectations which its predecessor gave me. &apos;Red Seas under Red Skies&apos; hasn&apos;t lived up to the heavenly high standards the &apos;Lies of Locke Lamora&apos; has set - instead, it was even better. </b><br/><br/><i>
  <blockquote>“Know something? I&apos;d lay even odds that between the people following us and the people hunting us, we&apos;ve become this cit</blockquote></i></span>
  <span id="freeText3516815020184661659" style="display:none">26/25 (104%) 5 stars.<br><b> Well. Whenever I've read an author's first book and simply adored it, like I did with Lynch's first, I'm really, really afraid that the next one won't live up to the high expectations which its predecessor gave me. 'Red Seas under Red Skies' hasn't lived up to the heavenly high standards the 'Lies of Locke Lamora' has set - instead, it was even better. </b><br><br><i>
  <blockquote>“Know something? I'd lay even odds that between the people following us and the people hunting us, we've become this city's principle means of employment. Tal Verrar's entire economy is now based on fucking with us.”</blockquote>
</i><br><br>I really took my time reading this one, and I was feeling very mixed after the first three chapters, because it seemed to be a plain heist story this time, but it wasn't. Lynch has once more written an absolute masterpiece which consists of a lot of swearing (yay!), helds more surprises than a box of Bertie Bott's Every Flavour Beans, and also once again features really, really, really bad character deaths. You seriously never (NEVER!) know what happens on the next page, and I absolutely love this in a book. Also, there's kittens.<br><br> <img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1548218633ra/26958079.gif" width="400" height="350" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><i>
  <blockquote>“Mew," the kitten retorted, locking gazes with him. It had the expression common to all kittens, that of a tyrant in the becoming. 'I was comfortable, and you dared to move,' those jade eyes said. 'For that you must die.' When it became apparent to the cat that its two or three pounds of mass were insufficient to break Locke's neck with one mighty snap, it put its paws on his shoulders and began sharing its drool-covered nose with his lips. He recoiled.'</blockquote>
</i><br><br>Plus, all of it is told in magnificent prose: the verbal sparring between Locke and Jean never ceases to amaze, ships, towns and people are presented so detailed that they become alive. Lynch has once again managed to create a world filled with people and places that leaves nothing to ask for, and the one thing he excells everyone else with is, once more, dialogue. Nobody, I tell you, nobody writes better dialogues than Scott Lynch. Period. <br><br><i>
  <blockquote>“That's a sweet piece," said Jean, briefly forgetting to be aggravated. "You didn't snatch that off a street."<br>"No," said Locke, before taking another deep draught of the warm water in the decanter. "I got it from the neck of the governor's mistress."<br>"You can't be serious."<br>"In the governor's manor."<br>"Of all the -"<br>"In the governor's bed."<br>"Damned lunatic!"<br>"With the governor sleeping next to her."<br>The night quiet was broken by the high, distant trill of a whistle, the traditional swarming noise of city watches everywhere. Several other whistles joined in a few moments later.<br>"It is possible," said Locke with a sheepish grin, "that I have been slightly too bold.”</blockquote>
</i> <br><br><b>What sets this one apart from other second sequels in many series is that Lynch changes basically the whole setting.</b> While ‚The Lies of Locke Lamora‘ was a heist and vengeance story set in something resembling Renaissance Venice, this one is for the biggest part a pirate story. That way, it feels just as fresh and original as the prequel. Easy, well-deserved 5 stars.<br>----<br>Dialogue 6<br>Setting 5<br>Characters 5<br>Writing Style 5<br>Plot 5</span>
  <a data-text-id="3516815020184661659" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


